00:31:25,346 --> 00:31:29,912
The design of the actual physical environment that you're in affects the story experience.

587
00:31:29,972 --> 00:31:34,278
For you as a writer for AR, how much of it goes into...

588
00:31:35,727 --> 00:31:39,890
I'm going to create an experience, how much goes into designing the actual environment

589
00:31:39,930 --> 00:31:45,614
and changing that, and how much of it is in whatever digital layer you're working with.

590
00:31:45,794 --> 00:31:49,236
So the question is, how much do we design the spaces and what impact does that have

591
00:31:49,276 --> 00:31:50,597
on the digital layer of storytelling?

592
00:31:50,997 --> 00:31:55,340
Actually in practice, most of the jobs that we've done so far as part of Playlines have

593
00:31:55,420 --> 00:32:01,263
been with relatively minimal set dressing, because we do it within existing spaces.

594
00:32:01,403 --> 00:32:04,085
So we'll take a museum, or a cultural center, or a park.

595
00:32:04,725 --> 00:32:09,067
And the idea is to not try to alter too much,

596
00:32:09,167 --> 00:32:11,268
because I'm interested in recontextualizing

597
00:32:11,348 --> 00:32:12,248
that environment.

598
00:32:12,428 --> 00:32:16,589
So we use what co-founder Dustin Freeman describes

599
00:32:16,609 --> 00:32:20,031
as reverse level design, where in conventional level design,

600
00:32:20,291 --> 00:32:22,271
you have the beats, you have the story you want to tell,

601
00:32:22,311 --> 00:32:23,292
and you build the environment.

602
00:32:23,512 --> 00:32:25,913
We start from the environment, and we work out

603
00:32:25,953 --> 00:32:28,934
the story from that place based on the opportunities

604
00:32:28,974 --> 00:32:29,454
that we see.

605
00:32:29,514 --> 00:32:31,775
Is there a natural fork in the environment for a decision?

606
00:32:32,055 --> 00:32:33,755
Is there a cool landmark or a nice little?

607
00:32:34,155 --> 00:32:37,779
Nook, we can talk players into to have an intimate experience.

608
00:32:38,199 --> 00:32:41,082
So a lot of what we currently do is reflecting on that.

609
00:32:41,142 --> 00:32:44,365
But that's also partly because those types of projects don't have the budget

610
00:32:44,385 --> 00:32:45,887
for a lot of on site set dressing.

611
00:32:45,987 --> 00:32:49,831
And also because they tend to be while creating an additional digital layer

612
00:32:49,851 --> 00:32:52,013
while the site is also in normal use.

613
00:32:52,593 --> 00:32:54,936
So we can't have too much of a physical footprint.

614
00:32:55,576 --> 00:32:58,419
